Below are two approaches to achieve the effect you’re after. In both cases the icon stays fixed at the bottom right of the page, and when a user hovers over it the icon “grows” or is swapped with a larger version.

---

### **Approach 1: Using CSS Transform (Scaling the Same Image)**

This method simply enlarges the icon on hover while keeping its bottom‑right anchor point fixed. It’s simple and smooth but uses the same image (scaled up).

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>WhatsApp Hover Icon (Scale)</title>
  <style>
    #whatsapp-link {
      position: fixed;       /* Keeps the icon in a fixed spot */
      bottom: 20px;          /* Distance from the bottom */
      right: 20px;           /* Distance from the right */
      z-index: 1000;         /* On top of other elements */
    }
    #whatsapp-link img {
      width: 50px;           /* Normal icon size */
      height: 50px;
      transition: transform 0.3s ease;
      transform-origin: bottom right; /* Ensures the bottom right stays anchored */
    }
    #whatsapp-link:hover img {
      transform: scale(1.4); /* Scales the icon to 1.4 times its original size on hover */
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <!-- Your webpage content here -->

  <!-- Clickable WhatsApp icon -->
  <a id="whatsapp-link" href="https://web.whatsapp.com/send?phone=1234567890" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <img src="path-to-your-whatsapp-icon.png" alt="Chat on WhatsApp">
  </a>

</body>
</html>
```

**Notes:**
- Replace `1234567890` with your phone number in international format (omit the “+” and any spaces).
- Replace `"path-to-your-whatsapp-icon.png"` with the actual path to your WhatsApp icon image.

---

### **Approach 2: Using Two Images (Swapping the Icon on Hover)**

This method uses two image files—one for the normal (smaller) state and one for the hover (bigger) state. The CSS toggles their visibility with a fade effect while keeping the button fixed.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>WhatsApp Hover Icon (Image Swap)</title>
  <style>
    /* Container for the clickable icon */
    #whatsapp-link {
      position: fixed;
      bottom: 20px;
      right: 20px;
      z-index: 1000;
      /* Setting a fixed area so the button doesn’t shift when images change */
      width: 50px;
      height: 50px;
    }
    /* Both images are positioned absolutely within the container */
    #whatsapp-link img {
      position: absolute;
      bottom: 0;
      right: 0;
      transition: opacity 0.3s ease;
    }
    /* Initially, only the small icon is visible */
    #whatsapp-link .big-icon {
      opacity: 0;
      width: 70px;   /* Big icon size */
      height: 70px;
    }
    #whatsapp-link .small-icon {
      width: 50px;   /* Small icon size */
      height: 50px;
      opacity: 1;
    }
    /* On hover, swap the visibility */
    #whatsapp-link:hover .small-icon {
      opacity: 0;
    }
    #whatsapp-link:hover .big-icon {
      opacity: 1;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <!-- Your webpage content here -->

  <!-- Clickable WhatsApp icon with image swap on hover -->
  <a id="whatsapp-link" href="https://web.whatsapp.com/send?phone=1234567890" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <img class="small-icon" src="path-to-small-icon.png" alt="Chat on WhatsApp">
    <img class="big-icon" src="path-to-big-icon.png" alt="Chat on WhatsApp">
  </a>

</body>
</html>
```

**Notes:**
- Update the `href` link with your own phone number (in international format, without the “+”).
- Replace `path-to-small-icon.png` and `path-to-big-icon.png` with the paths to your small and larger WhatsApp icon images.
- The container’s dimensions are set to match the small icon. The bigger icon is allowed to overflow (or you can adjust its positioning) so that the bottom right remains fixed.

---

Both approaches keep the icon immobile relative to the page and provide a visual cue when the user hovers over it. Choose the method that best fits your design requirements.
